INSERT INTO `cms_content` VALUES ('171', '172', '<div class=\"introduction\" style=\"margin:0px auto 3px;padding:10px 24px 10px 20px;vertical-align:baseline;overflow:auto;zoom:1;width:586px;border-width:1px 0px;border-top-style:solid;border-bottom-style:solid;border-top-color:#E5E5E5;border-bottom-color:#E5E5E5;background-color:#FBFBFB;line-height:24px;font-size:16px;color:#434343;font-family:微软雅黑, Tahoma, Verdana, 宋体;\"><p style=\"padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\">3月20日消息，<span style=\"font-weight:700;\">京东今日更新了递交给SEC的F1文件，披露了公司新的股权结构，目前腾讯持股数为351,678,637股，占总股本的14.3%，成为第三股东。</span>而刘强东获得93,780,970股普通限售股，旗下基金总股本数达463,345,349股，超越老虎环球基金成为第一大股东，占比为18.8%，投票权占51.2%。</p></div><div class=\"content\" style=\"margin:0px 10px 10px;padding:0px 10px;vertical-align:baseline;line-height:23px;min-height:150px;font-size:16px;overflow:hidden;font-family:微软雅黑, Tahoma, Verdana, 宋体;background-color:#FFFFFF;\"><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;text-align:center;\"><img alt=\"刘强东增持成京东第一股东 腾讯列第三\" src=\"http://static.cnbetacdn.com/newsimg/2014/0320/29_1jaCaYG1K.png\" original=\"http://static.cnbetacdn.com/newsimg/2014/0320/29_1jaCaYG1K.png\" style=\"border:0px;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-width:630px;\" /></p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;text-align:center;\">此前股权结构</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;text-align:center;\"><img alt=\"刘强东增持成京东第一股东 腾讯列第三\" src=\"http://static.cnbetacdn.com/newsimg/2014/0320/29_1jaCb2zei.png\" original=\"http://static.cnbetacdn.com/newsimg/2014/0320/29_1jaCb2zei.png\" style=\"border:0px;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-width:630px;\" /></p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;text-align:center;\">新的股权结构</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;\">3月10日，腾讯收购351,678,637股<a data-link=\"1\" href=\"http://count.chanet.com.cn/click.cgi?a=51684&amp;d=22815&amp;u=&amp;e=\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color:#003366;text-decoration:none;cursor:pointer;\">京东</a>普通股，占京东上市前在外流通普通股的15%，成为其一个重要股东，联姻后，京东保持独立。交易中，腾讯和京东资产将进行整合，腾讯<a data-type=\"2\" data-keyword=\"支付\" data-rd=\"1\" data-style=\"1\" data-tmpl=\"290x380\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color:#003366;cursor:pointer;\">支付</a>2.14亿美元现金，并将QQ网购，拍拍的电商和物流部门并入京东。而现阶段，京东会持易迅少数股权，并且同时持有未来独家全部认购权，易迅将继续独立品牌运营。除了资产外，腾讯将向京东提供微信和手机QQ客户端的一级入口位置及其他主要平台的支持，双方还将在在线支付服务方面进行合作。腾讯同时承诺不再进行若干电商业务。</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;\">而刘强东在3月也获得了93,780,970股普通限售股，使其持有的股本数由369,564,379增加至463,345,349，占比从18.4%增长至18.8%，一举超越老虎环球基金，成为第一大股东。由于AB股及部分基金将投票权让与，刘强东旗下基金的投票权由40.4%增长至51.2%，获得了公司的控股权。</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;\">老虎环球基金持股数未变，但由于股权稀释，其持有由22.1%降至18.1%。</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;\">除此之外，雄牛资本旗下基金也出现在京东的大股东行列，目前其持有53,640,484股，占比为2.2%。</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;\">不过沙特主权基金持股数已低于1%，原因未知，网易科技正与京东进行沟通。</p><p style=\"margin:8px auto 0px;padding:0px;vertical-align:baseline;word-wrap:break-word;line-height:26px;text-indent:2em;\">其他大股东持股数未发生变化。</p></div><p><br /></p>', '121502');
INSERT INTO `cms_content` VALUES ('172', '173', '<p><img src=\"http://dev-images.dodoedu.com/image/school_cms_121502_13964028836389-650.gif\" title=\"小猫_副本.gif\" />I&#39;ve been meaning to reply all week. </p><p>I basically concur with everyone else, but there are a few other things which haven&#39;t been mentioned:</p><p><br /></p><p>- what attracted you to Go?</p><p> * Initially, a particular combination of: far easier concurrency, no classical inheritance, rich &amp; consistent API, pragmatism, terseness/readability, along with static typing &amp; GC.</p><p> * Simple distribution: just a standalone, static binary (with straightforward support for cross-compilation). No need for interpreter/VM == no jar-hell/dll-hell, and no installation/maintenance of system-wide VMs in production. This is a massive one for me, but doesn&#39;t seem to attract that much adulation.</p><p> * Variables aren&#39;t pointers by default =&gt; far, far fewer Null Pointer type errors. This is big too.</p><p> * The platform is in very active development. Java has stagnated for so long.</p><p> * Less call for all the design-pattern bloat like AbstractSingletonProxyFactoryInstanceGeneratorBean.</p><p> * Distinct lack of XML-hell configuration (Java frameworks tend to have layers upon layers of XML configurations).</p><p><br /></p><p>- what parts are common to both languages?</p><p> * fast compiler, static typing, concurrency, GC</p><p><br /></p><p>- what parts you miss in Go?</p><p> * Some of the more mature parts of the Java ecosystem (e.g. IDEs; occasional GUI stuff like IzPack; version-enabled dependency management - i.e. Maven).</p><p><br /></p><p>- what parts you wish were part of Java?</p><p> * De-centralised package management, with package names locating dependencies. Very easy to get collaborating quickly. The Maven/Nexus/Central model is so much more work-intensive for collaboration, particularly when forking &amp; such. </p><p> * multiple return values.</p><p> * Implicit fulfilment of interfaces. Love it.</p><p> * GOPATH (much easier to manage than classpath. It just works)</p><p> * Go&#39;s source dependencies seem to be much easier to work with than binary (jar) dependencies.</p><p> * go fmt (yay for the standard format), go vet, go fix (upgrade facilitation FTW), go doc (e.g. Examples)</p><p><br /></p><p>Thanks for letting me get that off my chest :)</p><p><br /></p><p><br /></p><p>On Thursday, 13 March 2014 07:44:28 UTC+13, Francesc Campoy Flores wrote:</p><p>Hi Go nuts!</p><p><br /></p><p>I&#39;m doing some research and trying to better understand Java developers and their opinion on Go.</p><p><br /></p><p>I&#39;m interested in any feedback you could give, but specially on:</p><p><br /></p><p>- what attracted you to Go?</p><p>- what parts are common to both languages?</p><p>- what parts you miss in Go?</p><p>- what parts you wish were part of Java?</p><p><br /></p><p>Feel free to reply directly to me if you don&#39;t want to spam the whole list.</p><p><br /></p><p>Thanks!</p><p><br /></p><p>--</p><p>Francesc Campoy</p><p>http://twitter.com/francesc</p><p><br /></p>', '121502');
